• Reflecting • 

In order for me to have the opportunity to come back into the nursing program I needed to audit Fall Term. I also would have to chance there being a spot available for me winter term. I have successfully completed Fall Term as an auditor of my nursing program. I think it’s important to recognize that even though I had familiarity with this term, systems are always evolving. I came into the nursing program at the start of this term with a beginners mind. I’ve experienced adversity that has made me more resilient. I was able to adapt and grow through this. Having a new expectation the program had for me as an auditor allowed me to dive deeper into the topics we learned about. I was able to learn things with a new perspective. Reflecting back to the nursing student I was last year, I’ve grown tremendously, my instructors recognize that. I have a new profound confidence and drive. Through this growth, the support I’ve received from my program is unmatched. I am so grateful for the feedback I’ve received in continuing this growth. There was a part of me that was losing trust in this complex process and trust in myself. After successfully finishing the final, I can confidently say I am exactly where I am supposed to be. I am looking forward to continuing this journey winter term, and successfully completing the term I struggled the most in.

• The Journey • 
It has been such a journey to get to this moment. Not passing nursing school last winter term gave me so much perspective. It reminded me to let go of my “timeline” and let what is, be. That I will never miss what is meant for me. Although I’m still adapting to that mindset, I am grateful for where I am now. I passed my finals. I have the opportunity to move forth in my Nursing School journey. I see my growth. Nursing school is challenging, and now I continue where I left off with more knowledge and exponential growth ✨

Lucky to have gotten a dose of Kailee over this Spring Break! 🍀 This girl and I have gone through a lot together 💚 Long distant friendships are hard! Sometimes it feels like there’s not a lot of distance between us because we still show up for each other ✨ Lucky to connect with you kai when I get the opportunity to 💚 Miss you bunches! Xo

It’s beautiful to celebrate our differences. ❣️

This past weekend I attended my first National Foundation of Ectodermal Dysplasia’s conference in Denver, Colorado. It has taken me awhile to feel acclimated into the Ectodermal Dysplasia’s community due to not finding out I had it until I was 19 years old and knowing very little information about Ectodermal Dysplasia’s. I was denied access to genetic testing, but when I finally entered a “childbearing age” insurance considered it necessary. (This is problematic) I definitely would have benefited knowing I had this syndrome when I was much younger. Still to this day I feel like I missed out on many opportunities such as having a community, and knowing people who I could relate to. This mutation wasn’t researched until early 1997 so although I didn’t find out I had ED until I was 19, I am happy for the resources,  connections and knowledge I have now. This weekend I had the opportunity to meet one of the scientists from the Netherlands who has dedicated her life to researching about TP63 mutation. Despite not knowing I had a type of Ectodermal Dysplasia until my young adult years, getting to experience this conference was so informative and provided an opportunity to meet others with a TP63 mutation (for the first time). The most valuable thing I learned from the conference is even people who have TP63 mutation there is so much variation between each individual, this makes us unique.

•Year 2 Begins•
Nursing School is all about new opportunities, and advancing new skills professionally and personally. Tomorrow I continue this journey as a second year nursing student. It is bittersweet getting closer to the “finish line”. I can recognize that I still have so much to learn and I feel I have the tools to succeed. I’ve surprised myself on this journey of what I’m capable of. Yes, I have the first day of school nerves. I am also filled with gratitude that I have the opportunity to continue my education and be closer to fulfilling a dream. 🩺
